name: 2-bromophenylacetic acid
Reason: The basic unit for 2-bromophenylacetic acid is benzene, whose melting point is 5.5 degrees Celsius. The bromine atom, which is a heavy halogen, will likely increase the melting point significantly due to its added mass and the polarizability it contributes to the molecule. Estimating this effect as roughly +70 (considering a less pronounced effect than for boiling points due to solid-state intermolecular interactions). The acetic acid side chain (–CH2COOH) introduces both an alkyl chain and a carboxylic acid group. Alkyl chains can slightly lower the melting point due to increased flexibility of the molecule, but the carboxylic acid group will greatly increase the melting point due to strong hydrogen bonding. Combining these counteracting effects, we might estimate an overall increase of +50 for the acetic side chain. Adding these adjustments together, we have 5.5 (benzene) + 70 (bromine) + 50 (acetic side chain) = 125.5.
